### The `super` Keyword

The `super` keyword refers to the immediate parent class object. It is used to access parent class members.

---

### Uses of `super`

| Usage | Example |
|-------|---------|
| Access parent fields | `super.fieldName` |
| Call parent methods | `super.methodName()` |
| Call parent constructor | `super(parameters)` |

---

### Calling Parent Constructor

```java
class Animal {
    String name;

    Animal(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    Dog(String name) {
        super(name);  // must be first statement
    }
}
```

---

### Accessing Parent Methods

```java
class Animal {
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Animal makes sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() {
        super.sound();  // call parent version
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }
}
```

---

### Accessing Parent Fields

```java
class Parent {
    int value = 10;
}

class Child extends Parent {
    int value = 20;

    void display() {
        System.out.println(value);      // 20 (child)
        System.out.println(super.value); // 10 (parent)
    }
}
```

> **Key Point:** `super()` must be the first statement in the constructor if used. If you don't call `super()`, the compiler inserts a no-arg `super()` call automatically. The parent constructor must exist for this to work.

codeExample:
class Parent {
    String message = "Parent class";

    Parent() {
        System.out.println("Parent constructor");
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Display from Parent");
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    String message = "Child class";

    Child() {
        super();  // calls parent constructor
        System.out.println("Child constructor");
    }

    @Override
    void display() {
        super.display();  // call parent method
        System.out.println("Display from Child");
        System.out.println("Parent message: " + super.message);
        System.out.println("Child message: " + this.message);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Child c = new Child();
        c.display();
    }
}
